Building previously hidden moderators into a theory as boundary conditions can lead to overspecification and reduced parsimony.

New work by Johannes Ziegler and @mariogollwitzer.bsky.social 

Open Access: doi.org/10.1027/2151...

images.alt: In the wake of the replication crisis, it has been argued that many psychological theories do not sufficiently specify under which boundary conditions a hypothesized empirical effect occurs versus does not occur, which may explain why conceptual replications are sometimes unsuccessful. This reasoning implies that one path toward theory building is to identify all boundary conditions and to integrate them into the respective theory underlying the effect. In this article, we argue that identifying boundary conditions is undoubtedly worthwhile, but it comes with the risk of overspecifying theories. Overspecification occurs when certain assumptions of a hypothesis or theory can be dropped without noticeable loss in explanatory power. We argue that identifying boundary conditions for an effect to occur can be fruitfully combined with testing for overspecification of a hypothesis or theory. Such a combined strategy can improve cumulative theory building and, thus, increase the efficiency and integrability of psychological research.

This illustration depicts a man facing off against a giant dragon in a wilderness bathed in a fiery orange light. The entire background is lit by flames, making the air itself shimmer as if it were red-hot.

The man stands with his back to the viewer, his powerfully toned muscles highlighted by the firelight. A distinctive feature is the rabbit-ear-like ornament on his head (or perhaps the ears themselves), adding a humorous and soft impression to his heavy warrior-like armor. With a long sword hanging from his back and several tools and sheaths hanging from his waist, he is dressed as both a traveler and a warrior. The hem of his coat is fluttering wildly in the hot wind.

The dragon the man faces is so enormous that it overwhelms him. Its outline appears undulating and distorted against the background of a fiery red light that covers its entire body. The dragon's scales are a dark, heavy color, with glowing blue patterns scattered throughout, giving it a faint glow, as if magical power were lingering within. The face in particular has a strong blue light, which, combined with the red of the flames, gives it an eerie, mystical presence. The dragon's head has descended directly in front of the man, and the row of fangs in its mouth conveys a sense of power and danger.

The dragon undulates its body menacingly, while the man, weapon at the ready, meets its gaze in silence. Tension is building between the two, and the scene seems to capture the moment before battle is about to begin.

The overall illustration combines heat, the quiet determination of those facing each other, and the fantastic contrast of light, creating a powerful and dramatic effect.
